Ancient Civilization (2100 - 221 BCE): The earliest known Chinese civilization was the Xia Dynasty, which emerged around 2100 BCE. Over time, several other dynasties rose and fell, including the Shang, Zhou, Qin, Han, and Tang. These periods saw the development of writing, agriculture, trade, and governance.

Imperial China (221 BCE - 1912 CE): With the unification of China under the Qin Dynasty in 221 BCE, Imperial China began. This period lasted until the fall of the Qing Dynasty in 1912. During this time, China experienced significant cultural, economic, and political developments, such as the construction of the Great Wall, the invention of gunpowder, and the expansion of the Silk Road.

Modern China (1912 CE - present): In 1912, the Republic of China was established, marking the end of Imperial China. However, the country soon became embroiled in internal conflicts, foreign invasion, and social upheaval. In 1949, the Communist Party of China (CPC) took power, establishing the People's Republic of China. Since then, China has undergone rapid modernization, industrialization, and global integration, becoming one of the world's largest economies and most populous countries.

